				</ul>				
			</ul>	
	<p>
	You would add roles as best fits your company, the aim is the be able to break down the work to better identify workload
	and possible opportunities for improvement. If the roles are too high level, then no insight is gained, too low level and the 
	employees spend too much time recording effort which will have an effectt on efficiency and possibly morale.
	 Roles are not the employees, 
	so there is not a one to one relationship, e.g. you may have an sme role and 3 people in that role. 
	Typically in a small company many people will be multi-tasking, so some employees will cover a couple of roles in IT. 
	</p>
<%= link_to image_tag("openproject/roles1.png",:size => '450x500', alt: "Project Mgt"  ), class: 'centre' %>


<h5> Adding a New Role</h5>

<p>Once you have a list of roles you want to use in your projects, click the "newuser" on the right</p>

<%= link_to image_tag("openproject/roles2.png",:size => '450x500', alt: "Project Mgt"  ), class: 'centre' %>

<p>
I am going to copy another roles workflow as I add the roles
It is important that you set up workflow as this will have a large effect on how OpenProject works. 
For example, you may have a testing role. You may not allow the tester to create new tasks but you may 
allow them to change task from “in progress” to “feedback” or “rejected”. It will depend on the project framework 
you have setup in your company. You will also have to set up the permissions for all the new plugins for all 
the current default roles as well in this page.</p>

<%= link_to image_tag("openproject/roles3.png",:size => '450x500', alt: "Project Mgt"  ), class: 'centre' %>



<h5>Workflow</h5>
<p>
You do not have to change the default workflows. When you set up the new roles you copied current workflows. 
If you look at the developer workflow (press edit after you have selected the developer). 
You can see they have limited workflow, but it allows them to make comments and log their effort to the tasks that are assigned to them.
</p>

<%= link_to image_tag("openproject/workflow1.png",:size => '450x500', alt: "Project Mgt"  ), class: 'centre' %>
<p>Whereas the manager can control all the work packages and their status.</p>
<%= link_to image_tag("openproject/workflow2.png",:size => '450x500', alt: "Project Mgt"  ), class: 'centre' %>

<h5>Project Types</h5>
<p>
No Change to “Bug, “Feature”, “Support”, “Milestone” and “Phase”. 
If you decide to change these, then you will also have to reconfigure the roles and workflows, which is a large task, so not recommended.
</p>
<%= link_to image_tag("openproject/types1.png",:size => '450x500', alt: "Project Mgt"  ), class: 'centre' %>
<h5>Work Package Status</h5>
<p>
No Change to the defaults. If you change these, then you will have to revisit your 
Roles and Permissions and your workflow to enable the new status to function inside the application.
</p>
<%= link_to image_tag("openproject/workpackage1.png",:size => '450x500', alt: "Project Mgt"  ), class: 'centre' %>

<h5>Custom Fields</h5>
<p>Custom fields are not required for a simple implementation. If you integrate into your companies systems, 
	then you can use custom fields to match data, automate some reporting etc as well as track items that the business is specifically interested in.
</p>

<%= link_to image_tag("openproject/customfields1.png",:size => '450x500', alt: "Project Mgt"  ), class: 'centre' %>

